Lee:  The author makes many good points about power
with some good historical examples.  I enjoy the fact
that the federal government was actually *smaller*
in 1855 than in 1800.  Then (as the author says)
the Civil War came.

The author seems to imply that today it would be
possible for one to still knock on the front door
of the White House and be greeted by the butler
if only the Presidency hadn't become so powerful.

This is nonsense, of course.  Given modern transportation
and the fact that so many people have so much free time
on their hands, by 1880 the President of the U.S. (just
like the Governor of Alaska) would have to be beyond
reach.  Why, a few years back, you couldn't even knock
on Robert Heinlein's door a few miles south of here a
few years back.  Which is sort of obvious.

An important shift occurred after the invention of the
telegraph, and later was tremendously accelerated with
possibility of wars that could be all over in half an
hour.  Some systemic forces compel a nation's leadership
to be more focused.

Lee


